Let me trace through the logic:

1. User clicks "Open" → Expanded = true → OnExpandedParameterChangedAsync called → _state = Entering → StateHasChanged → CSS class changes to `mud-collapse-entering` which sets grid-template-rows: 1fr. This triggers a CSS transition on grid-template-rows.

2. The transition ends → transitionend event fires on the collapse container div → AnimationEndAsync called → _state is Entering, so it changes to Entered → OnAnimationEnd.InvokeAsync(true) is called. ✓ Correct.

3. Now _state is Entered. A button inside the collapse container has a hover animation (e.g., background-color transition). When the hover ends, transitionend fires → bubbles up to the collapse container → AnimationEndAsync called → _state is Entered, NOT Entering or Exiting → OnAnimationEnd.InvokeAsync(true) is STILL called! ✗ Bug!

So the fix is simple: only invoke OnAnimationEnd when _state actually transitioned (was Entering → Entered, or Exiting → Exited). In other words, only call OnAnimationEnd when _state was Entering or Exiting before being updated.

The fix:
```csharp
private Task AnimationEndAsync()
{
    if (_state == CollapseState.Entering)
    {
        _state = CollapseState.Entered;
        StateHasChanged();
        return OnAnimationEnd.InvokeAsync(_expandedState.Value);
    }
    else if (_state == CollapseState.Exiting)
    {
        _state = CollapseState.Exited;
        StateHasChanged();
        return OnAnimationEnd.InvokeAsync(_expandedState.Value);
    }

    return Task.CompletedTask;
}
```

This way, OnAnimationEnd is only called when the collapse/expand animation actually completes, not when child element animations complete.

